And this is 10 days into pre-orders.  The book officially comes out on August 29th.  I am so green in the book world that it has only just sunk in how truly remarkable selling 10k books this early is.

It's coming up on a year since I retired from burlesque.  For most of that time I have felt so much more focused and determined than I did before.  Removing this art from my life actually made space for me to accomplish so many things this year.  The split focus of being a content creator with being a burlesque instructor/producer/performer got to be too much for me.

But as time has gone on I have noticed how much I miss it.  Of course I miss the performers and I miss the audience but what I really miss is the purpose it gave me.  I always had something to work on or to talk about back then.  No matter what was occurring around me, burlesque gave me an outlet.  Something to focus on that wasn't my "public persona". Every Friday night I knew I would put on that glam makeup, do my hair and put on those pasties.  It was alot of work but it was consistent and omnipresent.

This also helped me to curate an online audience.  Burlesque is often not very palleteable for the mainstream, especially the radical queer verison that I brought to the stage.  So if folks started to tokenize me, they often pulled away when they saw my butt 🤣 However, I see more and more that I'm consumable to those who find themselves "centrists". So as a reminder I am and always will be a burlesque performer, I preach love and acceptance but I am and never will be a push over. 

So here is a photo to remind myself and all of you of this fact.  Sending you all love tonight, who knows where the next few months will take me.

As November and Trans Awareness Month comes to a close, I’d like to take a moment to discuss a vital community resource that may be overlooked. For some people the most accessible form of hormone therapy is the injectable kind, which comes with a whole new learning journey. New equipment and where to get it, nailing the technique, where to dispose of used supplies - it’s a lot to remember! Needle exchange services are community-based programs that provide clean supplies, help with safe disposal of used equipment, and provide links to other important services and programs. If you use injectable medication of any kind and don’t know where to dispose of your used equipment, you can look for information from your local Health Department on needle exchange services. These services are free and open to the public! Not only do these services help people on an individual level with free supplies, but they also help our communities by lowering the spread of hepatitis C and HIV.
If you’re local to the Madison, WI area @ViventHealth is one of our service providers. Tag your local exchange service below!
